The paper deals with distributed algorithms for consensus in networks, which is a topic in distributed computing and falls under the category of computer science - data structures and algorithms (cs.DS). The use of expanders and eigenvalues in the analysis suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the sub-category of computer science - social and information networks (cs.SI). The paper also involves information theory (cs.IT) in the analysis of the protocol's performance. The use of matrices and eigenvalues in the analysis suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the sub-category of computer science - systems and control (cs.SY). Finally, the paper's focus on consensus and opinion formation in networks suggests that it may also be relevant to the sub-category of computer science - neural and evolutionary computing (cs.NE).
